{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. With \HKQT98 you hold a broken sequence headed by the king-queen-ten, so lead the top of your sequence — the king — not a fourth-best.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 3\N. Count your tricks: 2 top \S, 1 \H (the lone ace), 2 top \D and 2 top \C — seven on top, so you need two more. The danger is West, who figures to hold long, strong \H behind your lone \HA with no quick entry; if West ever gets in, those \H run. Plan to hold up the \HA to cut East off, then build your extra tricks in \D and \C, where the finesses lose safely to East — and never touch the \S finesse, which would hand the lead to the danger hand.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK, which looks like top of a sequence, so West very likely holds the \HQ and a long suit behind it. Duck the first \H, and duck again if you can, to exhaust East of \H so the suit is dead if East ever wins. Then develop \D and \C: lead toward your honours and let any finesse lose into East — that's the safe hand. Between top cards and the established \D and \C you reach nine. The \S finesse is the trap: it loses to West's \SQ, and West cashes the \H — so leave \S alone beyond the two top winners.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Nine tricks: two \S, one \H, three \D and three \C, with West's \H neutralised. The whole hand turned on which way to lose the lead — you kept the dangerous West off play and steered every losing finesse into the safe East. Nicely judged avoidance.}
