{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. \HKQT85 is a broken sequence topped by the king-queen-ten, so you lead the top of the sequence — the king — rather than a fourth-best card.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 3\N. On top you have 2 \S, 1 \H (the lone ace), 2 \D and 2 \C — seven winners. West rates to sit with a long, strong \H suit over your single \HA and no side entry, so West is the hand you must keep out. Hold up the \HA, then run your long \C, where the suit develops with the lead losing only to East if at all; that brings home nine or more. Do not take the \S finesse — it loses to the wrong opponent.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK — top of a sequence, so West almost surely has the \HQ over you and a suit ready to cash. Duck once, ideally twice, to strip East of \H. Now attack \C: you have a long, strong holding that comes in for five tricks, and any loser falls to East, the safe hand. Two \S, one \H, two \D and the \C give you nine and more. Never finesse \S: West's \SQ wins and the \H cash out — clubs are the safe road home.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Made with the \C providing the bulk of the tricks while the held-up \HA kept West powerless. The key was refusing the tempting \S finesse and developing the suit that can only ever lose to safe East. Well played.}
