{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. Your \HKQT86 is a broken sequence headed by touching honors, so lead the top of it to drive out declarer's stopper and set up your long hearts.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 3NT. Count the top tricks: the \HA, two top spades, two top diamonds and two top clubs make seven. The danger is West's heart length — you hold only the \HA as a stopper, so if West ever gets in, the long hearts run and you are dead. The plan is to develop the SAFE suits: clubs (\CKJ8632 opposite \CA95) and diamonds, both of which lose, if at all, only to East. Set those up for five club tricks plus a third diamond, and NEVER take the spade finesse — finessing the \SJ would lose to West's \SQ, the danger hand.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK, which looks like top of a sequence, so West rates to hold the \HKQ over a long suit — the classic danger hand. HOLD UP the \HA: duck the first heart (and a second if they continue) to exhaust East of hearts, so East can never lead one back. Now go after clubs, where any loser is meant for safe East: lead toward dummy and finesse the \CJ — if it loses, it loses to East's \CQ, who has no heart to return. That brings in the club suit for five tricks; with the \HA, two spades and a diamond you are home with nine. Do NOT finesse the \SJ — that loses to West's \SQ and the hearts cash to beat you.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Nicely judged. The whole hand turned on refusing the tempting spade finesse and instead developing clubs, where any loser falls safely to East. Hold up the ace, keep the danger hand off lead, and let the safe opponent win — that is avoidance play in a nutshell.}
