[Auction "S"]
1N    Pass  3N    Pass
Pass  Pass
{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. With \HKQJ64 you have a powerful sequence — lead the top of it to knock out declarer's stopper and set up your long hearts.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 3NT. You start with the \HA, two top spades and two top clubs — five tricks. The danger is obvious: West has led from heart length and you hold a single stopper, so West cannot be allowed in. Your gold mine is clubs: \CKJT764 opposite \CA983 is a long, strong suit where any loser falls to East. Develop clubs for six tricks and you are home — \HA plus two spades plus six clubs is nine. Do NOT take the spade finesse; the \SJ would lose to West's \SQ and the hearts would crash down.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK, top of a sequence, so West almost surely holds the KQJ and a long heart suit — the danger hand. HOLD UP the \HA one round, then win, leaving East without a heart to return. Now run the club suit: with \CKJT764 opposite \CA983 you can finesse if needed, and the only club honour out, the \CQ, sits with safe East. Driving clubs gives you six tricks, and even if East wins a club he has no heart to lead, so the contract is secure. Never finesse the \SJ into West's \SQ — that is the single play that lets the hearts run.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Excellent. The long club suit was the whole answer: it provides plenty of tricks and any loser goes to harmless East. Hold up, develop the safe suit, and leave the spade finesse strictly alone — that is how you keep the danger hand from ever scoring its hearts.}
