[Auction "S"]
1N    Pass  3N    Pass
Pass  Pass
{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. Top of your \HKQJ954 sequence is the clear shot — force out declarer's stopper and establish your long hearts before your entry is gone.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 3NT. Top tricks: the \HA, two top spades, two top diamonds and two top clubs — seven. West has led heart length and you hold only the \HA, so West is the danger hand and must stay off lead. Build the last two in the SAFE suits: clubs (\CKJ765 opposite \CAT) for a fourth trick, finessing into East, and a third diamond, also losing only to East. Take just the two top spades — do NOT finesse the \SJ even though you hold \SKJ754, because that finesse loses to West's \SQ.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK, top of a sequence, so West rates to hold the KQJ over six hearts — the danger hand. HOLD UP the \HA: duck once and win the second round to clear East of hearts. Then develop clubs, leading toward dummy and finessing the \CJ — if it loses, it loses to East's \CQ, who can no longer hurt you. A third diamond, conceding only to East, brings the total to nine. Avoid the spade finesse: your \SKJ754 is tempting, but the \SJ finesse loses to West's \SQ and the hearts cash. Take your two top spades and look elsewhere for the rest.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Well done. The temptation was your long spades, but finessing there hands the lead to the danger hand. Holding up the ace and then developing clubs and diamonds — suits whose losers go to safe East — is the textbook avoidance line.}
